        <div class="section" id="section-3">
            <div class="section-title">Census vs. DNA-based Ne Comparison</div>
                
                <div class="comparison-grid">
            <div class="comparison-box census-box">
                        <div class="comparison-title">Census-based Ne Estimates</div>
                        <div class="step-details">
                            <strong>Method:</strong> Wright's formula using active breeding animals
                            <div class="formula short"><div class="formula medium">Ne = 4N<sub>m</sub>N<sub>f</sub>/(N<sub>m</sub> + N<sub>f</sub>)</div></div>
                            <strong>Advantages:</strong><br>
                            â€¢ Low cost, readily available data<br>
                            â€¢ Consistent methodology across breeds<br>
                            â€¢ Annual monitoring possible<br><br>
                            <strong>Limitations:</strong><br>
                            â€¢ Assumes idealized population<br>
                            â€¢ Ignores variable family sizes<br>
                            â€¢ Doesn't account for selection intensity<br>
                            â€¢ May overestimate genetic diversity
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="comparison-box dna-box">
            <div class="comparison-title">DNA-based Ne Estimates</div>
                        <div class="step-details">
                            <strong>Methods:</strong> Linkage disequilibrium (LD), inbreeding coefficients
                            <div class="formula short">Ne from LD decay patterns in genome</div>
                            <strong>Advantages:</strong><br>
                            â€¢ Reflects actual genetic diversity<br>
                            â€¢ Accounts for population history<br>
                            â€¢ More accurate for conservation decisions<br><br>
                            <strong>Limitations:</strong><br>
                            â€¢ Higher cost and technical requirements<br>
                            â€¢ Ascertainment bias in SNP arrays<br>
                            â€¢ Limited temporal coverage<br>
                            â€¢ Requires specialized expertise
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div style="background: #f8f9fa; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #e74c3c; margin-top: 20px;">
                    <strong>Key Finding:</strong> Census-based estimates were significantly higher than DNA-based estimates (p=0.0009). 
                    In 43 out of 53 comparisons, census methods overestimated Ne, with a median difference of 391 animals. 
                    This suggests that <span class="highlight">11% of breeds may appear genetically viable when they actually require conservation intervention</span>.
                </div>
            </div>
        <div class="section" id="section-2">
